In article <CLL4rx.2Hv@chinet.chinet.com> schneier@chinet.chinet.com (Bruce Schneier) writes:

 > I wish the publisher would be willing to correct the errors in the next
 > printing.  The problem is that Wiley considers it to be an expense that
 > won't help sales, so they are not interested.  

  Hmmm... The US is now a signatory to the Berne convention, and it
says that authors moral rights are non-transferable.  That means you
can forbid a reprinting for any reason, including that you don't want
them to reprint it with all the errors.

  That way, fixing the errors will help sales...

